{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"magna-carta-1215","type":"event","content":{"title":"Magna Carta Signed","date_label":"June 15, 1215","description":"On **June 15, 1215**, King **John of England** was forced by rebellious barons to seal the **Magna Carta** (*Great Charter*) at Runnymede. The document was originally a practical settlement of a feudal dispute — John was required to acknowledge specific rights of his barons and the Church and to refrain from arbitrary imprisonment.\n\nMost of its 63 clauses became obsolete within decades. But Clause 39 — *\"No free man shall be seized, imprisoned, dispossessed, outlawed, exiled or ruined in any way... except by the lawful judgement of his peers or by the law of the land\"* — became the foundation of the principle that the **law is above the sovereign**, and that arbitrary power has limits.\n\nThe Magna Carta's symbolic importance far exceeded its immediate practical effect. It became a touchstone for constitutional movements, was cited in the **English Bill of Rights**, influenced the **United States Constitution**, and remains one of the foundational documents of liberal democratic governance.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["magna-carta","john","england","constitution","rights","1215","law"],"sources":[{"title":"Magna Carta — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Magna-Carta"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"1215","precision":"day"},"significance":{"value":920,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"global"}}}
